Since \(\overline{AB} \parallel \overline{DE}\) and \(A\), \(C\), and \(E\) are collinear (as indicated by the diagram), triangles \(ABC\) and \(EDC\) are similar by the AA criterion. Given \(BD = 4BC\), we have \(BC:CD = 1:3\), so the linear scale factor from \(\triangle ABC\) to \(\triangle EDC\) is \(3\).

The area scale factor is the square of the linear scale factor: \(3^2 = 9\). Therefore, the area of \(\triangle CDE\) is \(9 \times \text{area}(\triangle ABC) = 9 \times 6 = 54\) square centimeters.

\boxed{54}

